      <Text layoutX="62.0" layoutY="184.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="1. Remove fat and silverskin off the top of the meat" />
      <Text layoutX="62.0" layoutY="215.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="2. No need to remove the membrane on the bone side.  It will help to keep the meat on the bones." />
      <Text layoutX="62.0" layoutY="256.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="3. Apply 1 tsp of salt per pound onto the meat and leave in fridge for 24 hours." />
      <Text layoutX="62.0" layoutY="291.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="4. This method is called dry brining and will help the the meat to retain moisture." />
      <Text layoutX="62.0" layoutY="327.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="5. Wet the meat with water and apply the rub all over." />
      <Text layoutX="62.0" layoutY="360.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="6. Start you fire with charcoal and add hickory wood." />
      <Text layoutX="62.0" layoutY="390.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="7. Maintain a temperature of 225 F" />
      <Text fill="#0c5263" layoutX="105.0" layoutY="416.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="note: Make sure there is no white smoke as this will produce a bitter unpleasant taste." />
      <Text fill="#0c5263" layoutX="135.0" layoutY="440.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="You want the smoke to be clear/bluish " />
      <Text layoutX="62.0" layoutY="470.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="8. Place rib bone side down and close the lid." />
      <Text layoutX="62.0" layoutY="503.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="9. Add a couple of Apple and Cherry wood chunks while maintaining 225 F" />
      <Text layoutX="62.0" layoutY="533.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="10. After 2 hours, open the lid and spray the ribs with a wet solution." />
      <Text fill="#0c5263" layoutX="105.0" layoutY="560.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="note:  Wet solution can be water, fruit juice, or apple cider vinegar.  Repeat this step every 45 minutes." />
      <Text layoutX="62.0" layoutY="592.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="11. Place a wired thermometer into the thickest part of the meat at this point." />
      <Text layoutX="62.0" layoutY="619.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="12. Cooking times vary depending on the thickness of the meat.  It may take between 5 to 10 hours." />
      <Text layoutX="62.0" layoutY="648.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="13. When the meat registers 203 F, it is done.  " />
